 time of 00:42 UTC on April 15th gives me roughly 6 hours and 40 minutes.\n\nThe cron:6f3323ef job started earlier at 22:59 UTC on April 14th, so it's been running for about 1 hour and 43 minutes by now.\n\nBoth jobs are active and doing periodic progress checks — one's the QLHV monitor that fires every 5 minutes, and the other is a DTLX progress monitor. I need to format a status report and send it to the Telegram session for the direct message to Lead.\n\nNow I'm checking the night silence window against the current UTC+7 time. It's 07:42 AM, which is past the 23:00-07:00 UTC+7 quiet hours, so I can go ahead and send the report. Looking at the session history, the previous status update was sent at 00:32 UTC, so this one at 00:42 UTC follows the normal 10-minute cadence. I'm also seeing that the cron:e7885813 session was the one that reported the status to the Telegram direct session, which is the one that just delivered the message. Continuing to calculate the uptime durations for the remaining cron sessions. For the ed2d0b5d session, the start time converts to 18:02 UTC, and the current time is 00:42 UTC the next day, giving a total runtime of about 6 hours and 40 minutes. The 6f3323ef session started at 22:59 UTC and has been running for approximately 1 hour and 43 minutes so far.\n\nNow I'm composing a status report to send to the Lead session, listing the two active cron jobs with their runtimes and descriptions, and noting that the pipeline is healthy with no blockers or active subagents.\n\nBut I'm second-guessing whether I should report at all—the cron session's message indicates it's running, but I need to verify if it's still actively processing or if it's already completed.","thinkingSignature":"42f6b52b56efff7ec986de2c6191ff5439c1861812df14521e70d6ea5f0b245e"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear picture. Two active master-orchestrator cron sessions (excluding this one), both healthy. Let me compile and send the status.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id"